statistically more robust (i. e. the standard error of the estimate is smaller). A Wald test rejects the
null hypothesis that the coefﬁcient is equal to zero at p < 0.01.
The speciﬁcation of the regression equation chosen by Janssen et al. (2011) essentially assumes
that position and round are metric variables, such that the coefﬁcients represent the slopes of a con-
tinuous, linear relationship. However, position and round are actually discrete variables that are more
appropriately included in the regression as factor variables (i. e., dummy batteries). We provide esti-
mates of this speciﬁcation in table 4. This is not only a technical issue, but we believe the results are
clearer and is easier to interpret. In particular, it uncovers that the effects for position E players are
much greater than for the other downstream players. In table 4 we also provide restricted maximum
likelihood estimates, which are more robust for the relatively small number of groups at hand.
Conclusion
The replication of the research claim of Janssen et al. (2011) was successful. The results not only
re-appear qualitatively but are quantitatively and statistically strengthened. The conclusions drawn
from the results are therefore robust, and the basic design can be conﬁdently used for follow-up re-
search.
